When given a token, anyone can upload a file to the URI `https://ws.api.video/upload?token=<tokenId>`.

Example with cURL:

```curl
$ curl https://ws.api.video/upload?token=toXXX -F file=@video.mp4
```

Or in an HTML form, with a little JavaScript to convert the form into JSON:
```html
<!--form for user interaction-->
<form name="videoUploadForm" >
  <label for=video>Video:</label>
  <input type=file name=source/><br/>
  <input value="Submit" type="submit">
</form>
<div></div>
<!--JS takes the form data 
    uses FormData to turn the response into JSON.
    then uses POST to upload the video file.
    Update the token parameter in the url to your upload token.
    -->
<script>
   var form = document.forms.namedItem("videoUploadForm");	
   form.addEventListener('submit', function(ev) {
	 ev.preventDefault();
     var oOutput = document.querySelector("div"),
         oData = new FormData(form);
     var oReq = new XMLHttpRequest();

     oReq.open("POST", "https://ws.api.video/upload?token=toXXX", true);
     oReq.send(oData);
	 oReq.onload = function(oEvent) {
       if (oReq.status ==201) {
         oOutput.innerHTML = "Your video is uploaded!<br/>"  + oReq.response;
       } else {
         oOutput.innerHTML = "Error " + oReq.status + " occurred when trying to upload your file.<br \/>";
       }
     };
   }, false);	
</script>
```


### Dealing with large files

This feature can be combined with [large file upload](https://api.video/blog/tutorial/video-upload-tutorial-large-videos).

After the first chunk is uploaded, the response contains a newly created `videoId` for this video.

You must inject it into the next requests as a form parameter. Our service will then be able to glue back together the pieces.

*Notice: When developing a HTML backend, some Javascript will be required to split the file and build the queries.*


#### CURL sample

Request/response 1:

```curl
curl https://ws.api.video/upload?token=toXXX \
  -H 'Authorization: Bearer eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImp0aSI6ImFiYjcxNmNiY2ZiNmY4MDc2OWEzZmQ1MjlhMjZiZWRkY2EwMzhlYzA3NDk5M2ZiMTA0YjhiZGMwOTI5MzgxN2M3NmNkNzI4ZDIzOGMzZmNlIn0..jWHC18iEur69FzD5dm78wAwNzh2cPKTRvKuspyQNQKPvhEbYa2v4XhqVNh0TTw8JeNxBtcePBTMHl4S9nWsw7pW4KD8zbqzUjCZNYlaYDpu8vu_tmWVO2JccglJIjuQEaiTbkUsfLdgtsb_9DJ3frk1-WgAKuzu0HewhcGb80xivdJPqNYA6I1Ig8GOief9LTUNNJoqqZn1A1-UiGRTXDag7_yODuxzpMFaAzbaisfK0gYti-PnjyHGWhpGwRplMKPPJk6rSAp1d9TWWXVgg-bNqUzz4_sr33ICJTx7_qZzfamMqk5PDZbHOwpIj8L2DBfo3isvt6QliWmgFEOuvog' \
  -H 'Content-Range: bytes 0-104857599/281905832' \
  -F file=@/path/to/file_chunk_aa
```

```json
{
    "videoId": "vitq4gOj8GyDT9kyxPQoyNJl",
}
```

After the first query is executed, the webservice generated a `videoId` and associated it with the first chunk. You must inject this `videoId` it into the next request.

Request/response 2:
```curl
curl https://ws.api.video/upload?token=toXXX \
  -H 'Authorization: Bearer {token}' -H 'Content-Range: bytes 104857600-209715199/281905832' \
  -F videoId=vitq4gOj8GyDT9kyxPQoyNJl
  -F file=@/path/to/file_chunk_ab
```

```json
{
    "videoId": "vitq4gOj8GyDT9kyxPQoyNJl",
}
```

Use the same technique for all remaining requests.'
